    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1791560094" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1791560094" />
    <a title="Krish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11962530-krish"><img alt="Krish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545985113p2/11962530.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1791560094?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Krish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Krish" href="/user/show/11962530-krish">Krish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788125904809" href="/book/show/204123.Freedom_at_Midnight">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1791560094" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1373923318142569455">This is an important book that reveals the fine-grained details that transpired during the transition of India from the British raj to an independent one. Like most historical non-fiction books, it inevitably suffers from biases, but that does not discount many of the facts presented. However one chooses to look at the events that unfolded, this book will reveal the highly complex and random nature of the process of India&apos;s freedom and the country&apos;s administration immediately thereafter. Some kn</span>
  <span id="freeText1373923318142569455" style="display:none">This is an important book that reveals the fine-grained details that transpired during the transition of India from the British raj to an independent one. Like most historical non-fiction books, it inevitably suffers from biases, but that does not discount many of the facts presented. However one chooses to look at the events that unfolded, this book will reveal the highly complex and random nature of the process of India's freedom and the country's administration immediately thereafter. Some knowledge and/or insights I acquired from this book:<br /><br />1) Mountbatten and Britain's task of transfer of power was a thanklessly complex one. Whether it was carried out in the best manner possible or not, the consequences had to be horrible for a large number of people. Even with the benefit of hindsight, one (or at least myself) can not predict whether it was right to:<br />a) expedite the process of power transfer,<br />b) not keep India undivided, and<br />c) help India get Kashmir, rather than let it remain independent or be taken by force by Pakistan.<br /><br />2) Nehru, Patel and other Indian leaders were understandably inexperienced in administration. If not for Britain's existing military organizations and the British administration's advice, the riots that plagued the aftermath of the partition might have had even more disastrous consequences than they did in actuality.<br /><br />3) Gandhi's role in quelling riots in Noakhali, Calcutta and Delhi was immense. If not for his peculiar obstinacy and saint-like adherence to principles of non-violence, many more innocent lives would have ended. At the same time, one wonders whether he unwittingly did sympathize with Muslim lives more than Hindu lives that led to his own demise as well as the anti-Muslim sentiment that got accentuated among extremist Hindus.<br /><br />4) Given the socialist welfare ideals of Nehru, the world lost a big opportunity to test the efficacy of decentralized administration the way Gandhi imagined for India. No top administrative official in India worked towards an India of self-sufficient villages with little dependence on materialism and a strong base in spiritual well-being. Maybe this is never practically possible, but I wish that a true believer in the ideals of Gandhi and not just the man himself had led the nation and tested his theory.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1373923318142569455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1791560094">
